node.contents: @aliteralmind I edited my answer to include some more detail on that point. It is kind of weird to think about, Integer being considered a supertype when realistically it can't be.

node.contents: The typing of T could be anything. Inside the class there is no way of knowing whether it's safe to put an Integer (int gets boxed here automatically) in the list or not. It's only safe to put a T in a List<T>.

astNode.text: The typing of T could be anything. Inside the class there is no way of knowing whether it's safe to put an Integer (int gets boxed here automatically) in the list or not. It's only safe to put a T in a List<T>.

node.contents: There won't be a way to add a concrete object to a generic list. The list must have a concrete type that definitely accepts Integer like List<Object>, List<Number> or List<Integer>.

astNode.text: There won't be a way to add a concrete object to a generic list. The list must have a concrete type that definitely accepts Integer like List<Object>, List<Number> or List<Integer>.

node.contents: Note that declaring that <T extends Integer> will not let you add an Integer to the list either. Integer is final but in an imaginary made-up Java where it's not, we could declare a Generator<IntegerSubtype> which would proceed to add an Integer to a List<IntegerSubtype>. This might later result in an Integer getting casted to an IntegerSubtype so it's not allowed.

node.contents: T is bounded but it's more obvious that the list may very well not be able to hold Object. Actually since Object has no superclass, an Object can't be put in anything except a List<Object>. By putting an Object in the list we might be (and probably are) later going to end up incorrectly downcasting it in to a subtype.
